WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.840
Hi everyone, thank you so much for coming. My name is Karishma, and today I'm going to be talking to you about simple machines, how to improve your workflows with APIs.

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:17.520
Okay, so show of hands, how many of you have ever heard or seen or built a Rube Goldberg machine before?

00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:22.240
Looks like most people in the audience. For those of you who have not,

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:27.520
a Rube Goldberg machine is a chain reaction type of machine or contraption that's intentionally

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:31.840
designed to perform a simple task in an indirect or overly complicated way.

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:37.040
When done successfully, it is a clean process with very little human intervention. Once it

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:41.759
gets started, it's efficient, it gives you a great output, and honestly, it's just super fun and

00:00:41.759 --> 00:00:47.840
satisfying to watch. These simple machines are also sort of similar to a data access pipeline,

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:53.439
from the point at which you access your data from the source and all of the intermediary steps that

00:00:53.439 --> 00:00:59.439
you take to get to your final output. So show of hands again, in your organizations, how many of

00:00:59.439 --> 00:01:06.000
you have data access pipelines that look as seamless as a Rube Goldberg machine? I see like

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:13.519
two hands. Okay, cool. We were in the exact same boat. How many of you, one click, okay,

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:16.800
instead have pipelines that look similar to this?

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:29.360
I'm not seeing as many hands as I would expect. Okay, there we go, that looks more like it.

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:33.919
Yeah, lots of manual intervention, lots of hiccups, you get the picture, and we found

00:01:33.919 --> 00:01:41.919
ourselves here as well. Okay, so today I wanted to share some lessons learned from our work at USAID

00:01:41.919 --> 00:01:46.879
on how we set up more efficient and automated systems to pull data through APIs to ultimately

00:01:46.879 --> 00:01:51.120
move ourselves along this spectrum from manual workflows to a more automated system.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:57.519
As a caveat, we are not data engineers, we are a team of data scientists and public health

00:01:57.519 --> 00:02:02.400
professionals who found ourselves stuck in a series of analytic loops of inefficient data

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:08.000
practices, and wanted to share with you today some of the small ways and tools that we've built

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:14.399
to overcome these problems in our work. So my name is Karishma Srikanth, I'm a data analysis advisor

00:02:14.399 --> 00:02:19.279
at the U.S. Agency for International Development, working in the Office of HIV-AIDS under the

00:02:19.279 --> 00:02:25.119
President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief, also known as PEPFAR. It's a mouthful. This presentation

00:02:25.119 --> 00:02:29.839
was developed in collaboration with my colleague, Aaron Chaffetz, who was unable to travel for the

00:02:29.839 --> 00:02:36.320
conference this time, but huge thanks to him for all of his work to get this presentation ready.

00:02:37.199 --> 00:02:41.440
So to give you some background on where we work, our work supports PEPFAR, which is a six billion

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:47.839
dollar HIV-AIDS program. Our team at USAID analyzes, synthesizes, and visualizes large

00:02:47.839 --> 00:02:53.679
amounts of monitoring and evaluation health data from over 55 countries worldwide. So that's a lot

00:02:53.679 --> 00:02:59.679
of data and a lot of context to ultimately inform HIV programming and move the needle to ending HIV

00:02:59.679 --> 00:03:05.600
as a public health threat. When we were standing up our analytic infrastructure, we faced four key

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:12.399
roadblocks. Firstly, as you saw, we have a really, really large scope. We have data coming in from

00:03:12.399 --> 00:03:18.559
various different external systems, often in non-standard formats, from static CSVs to messy

00:03:18.559 --> 00:03:24.880
Excel sheets to the occasional pull from a database. On top of that, we found ourselves in a series of

00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:30.240
analytic loops, frequently receiving similar analytic requests each quarter, and we often

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:34.960
found ourselves addressing those requests in a really manual, repetitive, and redundant way.

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:40.399
Finally, in a government environment, we lacked a centralized data lake to manage these data

00:03:40.399 --> 00:03:45.600
processes. So we found ourselves doing these manual processes each time without a standardized

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:50.720
infrastructure to make it a little bit easier for ourselves. So when we were beginning to think

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:54.479
about ways that we wanted to make our workflows more efficient, we knew we wanted to move across

00:03:54.559 --> 00:03:58.800
the spectrum from manual to automated. But importantly, we also needed to consider the

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:04.479
axis of accessibility, ensuring that all the processes and tools that we built were meeting

00:04:04.479 --> 00:04:10.320
the needs of all of the users in our organization. For instance, a highly automated but complex

00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:16.079
infrastructure, while powerful, would be incredibly costly and time-consuming and potentially

00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:22.480
prohibitive for new users to actively engage with. Conversely, a highly complex manual system is sort

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:27.519
of the worst of both worlds, requiring a lot of specialized expertise and knowledge that's not

00:04:27.519 --> 00:04:33.200
necessarily scalable to a broader organization. We most frequently found ourselves here in the

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:38.880
upper left-hand quadrant, with analytic workflows that were stood up sort of to respond reactively

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:44.160
to requests, that were manual but accessible in nature to a lot of people in our organization.

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:48.720
And so our goal was to leverage APIs strategically to move ourselves in this direction of the upper

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:55.839
right-hand quadrant, optimizing for accessibility and automation. So I want to take you through four

00:04:55.839 --> 00:05:00.480
key lessons that our team learned through this journey of leveraging APIs for our data access.

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:06.320
The first lesson is to keep it small to start. A small but effective simple machine, like these

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:11.519
dominoes falling in a circle here, are far more impressive than an intricate machine that might be

00:05:11.519 --> 00:05:17.359
prone to error and takes a lot of time to stand up. So typically in our work, when we are introduced

00:05:17.359 --> 00:05:22.320
to a new data source or a new problem, we start by seeing all of the possibilities and start to

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:26.880
think really big about all of the ways that we can address this problem and the big things that we can

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:32.160
build. However, we can't emphasize enough how important it was for us to keep our focus really

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:38.480
small to start, and then set some of those larger ambitions aside, fail fast and small, and solve the

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:43.839
basic problem at first in a way that allows us to scale this more broadly in the future.

00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:48.160
So I want to take you through one of the first examples that our team embarked on

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:53.359
to routinize our data access with an API. So on the left-hand side here, you'll see a screenshot

00:05:53.359 --> 00:05:58.799
of one of our internal PEPR data systems called Datum. And this houses all of our quarterly

00:05:58.799 --> 00:06:04.160
monitoring and evaluation data from over 50 countries. So in this data system, you can pull

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:08.160
various different health indicators for various different countries all the way down to a health

00:06:08.959 --> 00:06:15.760
facility level if you wish. But as you can probably tell, it's incredibly cumbersome to use.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:21.440
A lot of point and click. You have to sort of drag these indicators into a pane, toggle them on and

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:25.119
off. And then you can't remember what you did when you come back to it in a couple of days.

00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:32.160
And so this scope was really vast. This is one of our most common data systems. Everyone in

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:36.320
our organization uses it. So there were lots of different use cases that we thought of

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:41.760
that we could use to make these systems more efficient. However, in the spirit of keeping

00:06:41.760 --> 00:06:46.399
things small, we first wanted to tackle the question of how do we build an API to query this

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:54.239
without basically any documentation to do so. So on the right-hand side there, you will see

00:06:54.880 --> 00:07:02.320
our just like basic code chunk that queries this API. So we use the glue package to pull in the URL

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:08.480
for this API. And then use functions from the HTTR package, the get functions to create a get

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:15.519
request to query this URL. And also authenticate with our internal credentials. So from here,

00:07:15.519 --> 00:07:19.359
once we had this as our framework, we had to figure out how to package this up in a way that

00:07:19.359 --> 00:07:24.160
was actually useful to all of the people in our organization to work with. Which was really

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:28.000
challenging. Because you can take a really simple request, but then you need to think about how do

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.320
I parameterize this and put it into a function with all of the different ways that someone can

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:37.679
use this. But by keeping it small and going through the series of trial and error in this

00:07:37.679 --> 00:07:41.920
more focused way, we were able to figure out how to make this simple solution dynamic and

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:47.519
generalizable to a broader audience. So this code chunk sort of became the start of a framework

00:07:47.519 --> 00:07:52.480
that ultimately became an R package that was completely dedicated to accessing our data

00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:58.239
systems through an API. The second lesson was to minimize the manual. And by that, I mean,

00:07:58.239 --> 00:08:04.320
limit your clicks. If your simple machine requires a lot of manual intervention, like a kid pushing

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:09.760
a train down a train track, it can be prone to error, not likely to be sustainable, and can be

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:16.000
costly to run. So by identifying and setting up APIs for data access, we can create a lot of time

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.640
savings and speed up our production, allowing us to actually focus on some of the key components

00:08:20.640 --> 00:08:26.320
of our project rather than getting bogged down in the processing. Also, by reducing the cost

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:31.839
of accessing this data, we can promote better data accessibility and lead to greater usage of

00:08:31.839 --> 00:08:37.440
these data. So here's another example from our work using an external data system to our

00:08:37.440 --> 00:08:44.000
organization. This here is a Shiny app that houses publicly available epidemiological estimates that

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:49.280
come from UNAIDS, which is a UN agency that focuses on HIV. And so this offers a glimpse

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:53.840
across a lot of different countries about what the HIV epidemic looks like by country. So it's

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:59.440
things like prevalence, how many people are on HIV treatment, et cetera, all really key metrics for us

00:08:59.440 --> 00:09:04.799
to understand programmatically and from a target setting perspective. So similar to the previous

00:09:04.799 --> 00:09:09.919
example, pulling data out of this system requires a lot of clicks and manual downloads. And you'll

00:09:09.919 --> 00:09:14.159
see here in this video, the most cumbersome part is that if you are trying to pull multiple

00:09:14.159 --> 00:09:20.000
different indicators, you sort of have to go through, pick everything you want, change it over

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.559
to a table, click the CSV, and then go back and do it all over again for everything else that you're

00:09:24.559 --> 00:09:30.719
asking for. So it's a pain, especially when you're asked for a rapid request across multiple different

00:09:30.719 --> 00:09:40.159
indicators. So we use APIs to solve this iteration problem. We figured out the API, the URL from this

00:09:40.159 --> 00:09:46.000
API, and identified the dynamic components of this URL, like the indicator or age group, and used

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:53.119
the paste zero function to dynamically change the input URL within this function based on whatever

00:09:53.119 --> 00:09:57.840
the user is inputting. So this function here essentially does exactly what was shown on the

00:09:57.840 --> 00:10:03.200
previous slide. It just pulls things out of the Shiny app. We then took this a step further and

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:08.400
leveraged packages like purr from the tinyverse with these API functions to make it easier to

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:13.919
pull data across multiple different indicators, countries, and population groups. And ultimately,

00:10:13.919 --> 00:10:18.640
both of these functions are in the process of being packaged up into a package called Mind the

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:24.080
Gap up in the top right-hand corner, which is entirely focused on projects related to these

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:30.799
estimates. So the upshot here is by keeping it small and by focusing on the key components of

00:10:30.799 --> 00:10:35.520
this process that were sort of a pain because of how manual they were, we were able to build a

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:40.159
really simple tool to increase the accessibility of these data and ultimately ease of use.

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:46.799
The third lesson is to use what you have, and this one's pretty self-explanatory. Rather than going

00:10:46.799 --> 00:10:51.840
out and buying a bunch of equipment to build your machine, use what you have at your house. And by

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:56.960
that, I mean use the infrastructure that your organization has set up. And this can be quite

00:10:56.960 --> 00:11:01.599
challenging. For our organization in particular, we didn't have a database that we could tap into

00:11:01.679 --> 00:11:06.799
and really leverage. Instead, we were limited to the Google Suite, which is not a database. But

00:11:06.799 --> 00:11:12.080
given that that was the environment that we were working in, we can use it more strategically to

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:17.359
optimize our workflows. So whenever we can, we try to tap into the Google API and the Tinyverse

00:11:17.359 --> 00:11:22.960
packages like Google Drive and Google Sheets 4 to routinize our data access, but also just promote

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:29.919
good documentation and project management guidelines, like setting up project folders

00:11:30.479 --> 00:11:35.200
and using Google Forms to collect data rather than just having manual submissions.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:39.760
So in this example, in addition to some of the quarterly data systems that I've shared with you

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:46.159
today, we also collect what's called high-frequency reporting data, which is just another way of

00:11:46.159 --> 00:11:50.559
saying monthly data submissions that are coming from our country teams that allow us to have a

00:11:50.559 --> 00:11:55.200
more granular level of how the HIV program landscape is happening on a month-to-month basis.

00:11:55.200 --> 00:12:00.400
So in the past, the way the system would work is we had over 30 countries that were reporting

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:07.039
this data to our office in DC, and they would email us their Excel files, and we would kind

00:12:07.039 --> 00:12:13.359
of have to sift through our email, pull down all of these submissions that were emailed to us,

00:12:13.359 --> 00:12:18.880
pull them into R, process them, validate them, and then manually push them back up to the Google

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:25.119
Drive. So super cumbersome. It was a pain. However, leveraging the Google API really,

00:12:25.119 --> 00:12:30.479
really changed the way that we approached this problem. Instead of having these submissions be

00:12:30.479 --> 00:12:36.080
emailed, these were submitted to us via a Google Form, and then as you know, with a Google Form,

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:41.119
the metadata gets stored into a Google Sheet, so we were able to use the Google API to query those

00:12:41.919 --> 00:12:47.200
data submissions from our country teams directly, pull them into our R environment, work with them,

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:53.200
process, validate all those fun things, and then push up our documentation through an R Markdown

00:12:53.200 --> 00:13:00.080
or Cordo file. So just simply working within the infrastructure we have and identifying what those

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:05.200
key metrics were that were causing a little bit of backlog and manual work ended up completely

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:13.200
revolutionizing the way that we approached this problem. So the final step is to package it all up.

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:18.479
So using all of these lessons, keeping it small, reducing your manual, using the infrastructure

00:13:18.479 --> 00:13:24.000
you have, the next step is to take all of that awesome work that you did and build a package

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.799
and documentation for your organization to store these generalized solutions. Packaging up your

00:13:28.799 --> 00:13:33.119
work based on your workflows should be flexible in nature to meet the organization's needs,

00:13:33.119 --> 00:13:37.359
but also kind of speak the language of your organization so that it's more broadly accessible

00:13:37.359 --> 00:13:43.119
to every user in your organization. That allows you to solve problems in a more streamlined fashion

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:47.119
as they arise going forward because you've done all the upfront work to document.

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:54.080
So in our case, all of the examples that I shared with you today ended up as some kind of R package.

00:13:54.080 --> 00:14:00.000
Some of them, like Grabber and Glamour off to the left-hand side, are more just utility packages

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:06.239
that were designed to house functions that just improve our workflows from project setups to

00:14:06.239 --> 00:14:11.200
querying our databases with APIs. All of these functions are stored here and they just work

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:16.960
and can be scaled to a lot of our different projects. Others, like Mind the Gap and HFR,

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:22.239
are more project-specific and were tailored to a specific need, an analytic question that we had,

00:14:22.239 --> 00:14:27.840
that can then be more broadly generalized if need be. So these are just four of the almost 15

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:32.799
packages that our team maintains for our organization and work. If you're interested

00:14:32.799 --> 00:14:36.640
in learning a little bit more about the work that we've done, our packages are linked at the bottom

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:43.119
of this slide. So just as a recap, when thinking about ways to improve efficiencies in your work

00:14:43.119 --> 00:14:48.479
and potentially use APIs to improve your data access, the lessons are to keep it small to start,

00:14:49.039 --> 00:14:54.640
minimize your manual steps, and identify what those are to functionalize them more appropriately.

00:14:55.679 --> 00:15:00.320
The third is to use the infrastructure and environment that you have, and fourth, to package

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:05.280
it up and document. These solutions are not a one-size-fits-all approach and will look different

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:11.039
for every organization. However, it was really key for us to sort of challenge the status quo of how

00:15:11.039 --> 00:15:16.080
we've always done things just because they were easy and stood up at the time and pushed for ways

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:21.440
to automate. And it created enormous time savings and got us back to focusing on the questions

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:25.520
and key program areas that we really wanted to be focusing on with our data.

00:15:27.679 --> 00:15:31.840
As we wrap up, let's just bring this back full circle to where we started with the Rube Goldberg

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:38.640
machine. It's an elegant yet complicated solution to a simple problem. But as we've discussed today,

00:15:38.640 --> 00:15:43.039
our goal in managing our data workflows is to sort of simplify and streamline the process on

00:15:43.039 --> 00:15:47.440
the whole. We shouldn't want to have to think about it any more than we already do. So by applying

00:15:47.440 --> 00:15:51.840
some of these lessons we've learned, we can avoid building an overly complicated and error-prone

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:56.559
machine and instead build something that's reliable, efficient, and ultimately more impactful,

00:15:56.559 --> 00:16:02.640
and it just works. So as you return to your projects, consider if you are building an

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:06.719
intricate machine or sort of just working within the status quo, or if there are ways that you can

